Roman Law, p. 3¹0· By the side of the jurists who had authority in questions of civil law are mentioned the pontifices and augurs, who had the superintendence of what we may call ecclesiastica] law (for the ius augurium, see note on 12, p. 6, l. 6). The ius pontificium, exercised by the college of pontifices, had authority in the entire field of religious institutions, except so far as foreign rites were under the superintendence of the quindecimviri sacris faciundis, who had charge of the Sibylline Book5. The Pontifex Maximus was therefore the head of the ecclesias- tical institutions of Rome: this office was conferred upon Augustus, as a regular part of the functions of the Emperor, who by this act became head of Church as well as of State. This combination of supreme civil and ecclesiastieal powers continued until the Christian emperors,
